tables.description: The audit_checks table represents a record of regular audits performed across various sites. It stores information about the audit date, the auditor who conducted the audit, and the audit score obtained. This table is typically used in analytics and business workflows to track compliance and identify areas for improvement.

columns.description: The audit_pk column represents a unique identifier for each audit record, serving as a primary key for the audit_checks table. It stores integer values, indicating the primary key for each audit record. This column is crucial for uniquely identifying each audit record and facilitating data retrieval and analysis.

The site_fk column represents the foreign key referencing the site_master table, indicating the site associated with each audit record. It stores integer values, linking each audit record to the corresponding site. This column is essential for tracking audit records by site and facilitating site-level reporting and analytics.

The audit_dt column represents the date on which each audit was performed. It stores date values, indicating the audit date for each record. This column is crucial for tracking audit records over time and facilitating data analysis and reporting.

The auditor column represents the name of the person who conducted each audit. It stores character varying values, indicating the auditor's name for each record. This column is essential for tracking audit records by auditor and facilitating auditor-level reporting and analytics.

The audit_score column represents the score obtained by each audit. It stores integer values, indicating the audit score for each record. This column is crucial for tracking audit scores over time and facilitating data analysis and reporting.

tables.description: The event_log table captures significant events that occur within the organization, including staff activities and system events. It stores information about the event date, the staff member involved, and the risk level associated with the event. This table is crucial for auditing and monitoring purposes, helping to identify potential security threats and areas for process improvement.

columns.description: The event_pk column represents a unique identifier for each event record, serving as a primary key for the event_log table. It stores integer values, indicating the primary key for each event record. This column is essential for uniquely identifying each event record and facilitating data retrieval and analysis.

The staff_fk column represents the foreign key referencing the staff table, indicating the staff member involved in each event. It stores integer values, linking each event record to the corresponding staff member. This column is crucial for tracking event records by staff member and facilitating staff-level reporting and analytics.

The event_dt column represents the date on which each event occurred. It stores date values, indicating the event date for each record. This column is essential for tracking event records over time and facilitating data analysis and reporting.

The event_category column represents the category of each event. It stores character varying values, indicating the event category for each record. This column is crucial for tracking event records by category and facilitating category-level reporting and analytics.

The risk_level column represents the risk level associated with each event. It stores integer values, indicating the risk level for each record. This column is essential for tracking risk levels over time and facilitating data analysis and reporting.

tables.description: The learning_records table stores information about the training and development activities of staff members. It contains details about the course name, completion status, and the date the course was completed. This table is essential for tracking staff development and identifying areas where additional training is required.

columns.description: The learning_pk column represents a unique identifier for each learning record, serving as a primary key for the learning_records table. It stores integer values, indicating the primary key for each learning record. This column is crucial for uniquely identifying each learning record and facilitating data retrieval and analysis.

The staff_fk column represents the foreign key referencing the staff table, indicating the staff member involved in each learning record. It stores integer values, linking each learning record to the corresponding staff member. This column is essential for tracking learning records by staff member and facilitating staff-level reporting and analytics.

The course_name column represents the name of the course completed by each staff member. It stores character varying values, indicating the course name for each record. This column is crucial for tracking learning records by course and facilitating course-level reporting and analytics.

The course_dt column represents the date on which each course was completed. It stores date values, indicating the course completion date for each record. This column is essential for tracking learning records over time and facilitating data analysis and reporting.

The completion_status column represents the status of each course completion. It stores character varying values, indicating the completion status for each record. This column is crucial for tracking learning records by completion status and facilitating completion status-level reporting and analytics.

tables.description: The org_units table represents the organizational structure of the company, including departments, teams, and other units. It stores information about the unit title, site affiliation, and the head of the unit. This table is used to manage organizational hierarchies and facilitate communication between different units.

columns.description: The unit_pk column represents a unique identifier for each organizational unit, serving as a primary key for the org_units table. It stores integer values, indicating the primary key for each unit. This column is essential for uniquely identifying each unit and facilitating data retrieval and analysis.

The unit_title column represents the title of each organizational unit. It stores character varying values, indicating the unit title for each record. This column is crucial for tracking unit records by title and facilitating unit-level reporting and analytics.

The site_fk column represents the foreign key referencing the site_master table, indicating the site associated with each unit. It stores integer values, linking each unit record to the corresponding site. This column is essential for tracking unit records by site and facilitating site-level reporting and analytics.

The unit_head column represents the head of each organizational unit. It stores character varying values, indicating the unit head for each record. This column is crucial for tracking unit records by head and facilitating head-level reporting and analytics.

The created_on column represents the date on which each unit was created. It stores timestamp values, indicating the creation date for each record. This column is essential for tracking unit records over time and facilitating data analysis and reporting.

tables.description: The site_master table contains information about the various sites operated by the organization. It stores details about the site title, nation, region, and the date the site was created. This table is used to manage site-level data and facilitate site-specific reporting and analytics.

columns.description: The site_pk column represents a unique identifier for each site, serving as a primary key for the site_master table. It stores integer values, indicating the primary key for each site. This column is crucial for uniquely identifying each site and facilitating data retrieval and analysis.

The site_title column represents the title of each site. It stores character varying values, indicating the site title for each record. This column is essential for tracking site records by title and facilitating site-level reporting and analytics.

The nation column represents the nation associated with each site. It stores character varying values, indicating the nation for each record. This column is crucial for tracking site records by nation and facilitating nation-level reporting and analytics.

The region column represents the region associated with each site. It stores character varying values, indicating the region for each record. This column is essential for tracking site records by region and facilitating region-level reporting and analytics.

The created_on column represents the date on which each site was created. It stores timestamp values, indicating the creation date for each record. This column is crucial for tracking site records over time and facilitating data analysis and reporting.

tables.description: The staff table represents the personnel working within the organization. It stores information about the staff member's full name, unit affiliation, role, and joining date. This table is essential for managing staff data and facilitating communication between different departments.

columns.description: The staff_pk column represents a unique identifier for each staff member, serving as a primary key for the staff table. It stores integer values, indicating the primary key for each staff member. This column is essential for uniquely identifying each staff member and facilitating data retrieval and analysis.

The staff_fullname column represents the full name of each staff member. It stores character varying values, indicating the staff member's full name for each record. This column is crucial for tracking staff records by name and facilitating staff-level reporting and analytics.

The unit_fk column represents the foreign key referencing the org_units table, indicating the unit affiliated with each staff member. It stores integer values, linking each staff record to the corresponding unit. This column is essential for tracking staff records by unit and facilitating unit-level reporting and analytics.

The role_name column represents the role of each staff member. It stores character varying values, indicating the staff member's role for each record. This column is crucial for tracking staff records by role and facilitating role-level reporting and analytics.

The joining_date column represents the date on which each staff member joined the organization. It stores date values, indicating the joining date for each record. This column is essential for tracking staff records over time and facilitating data analysis and reporting.
